Suicidality and Coping in Male Veteran Sample with SMI

library(tidyverse)
library(rstanarm)
library(GGally)
library(corrplot)

Read Jahn data:

setwd("/Users/peterphalen/Downloads/JAHNDATA/")
dat <- read_csv("suicide_combined_all.csv")

Peprocessing

I only care about COPE data so I restrict the sample to the 50 people with COPE data and then calculate all its subscales:

# restrict to people with complete COPE data
dat <- dat[which(dat$cope_complete == 2),]
dat <- within(dat,
       {
       positive.reinterpretation.and.growth = cope_1 + cope_29 + cope_38 + cope_59
       mental.disengagement = cope_2 + cope_16 + cope_31 + cope_43 
       focus.on.and.venting.of.emotions = cope_3 + cope_17 + cope_28 +cope_46
       instrumental.social.support = cope_4 + cope_14 + cope_30 + cope_45
       active.coping = cope_5 + cope_25 + cope_47 + cope_58
       denial = cope_6 + cope_27 + cope_40 + cope_57
       religious.coping = cope_7 + cope_18 + cope_48 + cope_60
       humor = cope_8 + cope_20 + cope_36 + cope_50
       behavioral.disengagement = cope_9 + cope_24 + cope_37 + cope_51
       restraint = cope_10 + cope_22 + cope_41 + cope_49
       emotional.social.support = cope_11 + cope_23 + cope_34 + cope_52
       substance.use = cope_12 + cope_26 + cope_35 + cope_53
       acceptance = cope_13 + cope_21 + cope_44 + cope_54
       suppressing.competing.activities = cope_15 + cope_33 + cope_42 + cope_55
       planning = cope_19 + cope_32 + cope_39 + cope_56
       })

# To avoid retyping the scale names a bunch of times, we save a vector containing the names of all the subscales
cope.subscales <- c("positive.reinterpretation.and.growth",
                    "mental.disengagement",

Create some basic demographic variables.

dat$marital <- factor(dat$marital, levels=1:4, labels=c("married","widowed","divorced","single"))
dat$race <- factor(dat$Race, levels=1:7, labels=c("AmerInd","AsianPI","AsianPI","Black","AsianPI","White","Multiple"))
dat$gender <- factor(dat$male, 0:1, labels=c("female","male"))

Take a look at depression distribution, which well also want to include in multivariate analyses.

ggplot(dat) + 
  aes(x=FCESD) + # depression
  geom_bar()

And heres the distribution of suicidal ideation in the sample, as measured by the Beck Scale for Suicide Ideation (BSS). About half the sample has some level of suicidal ideation.

ggplot(dat) +
  aes(x = BSS_sum) +
  geom_bar()

Log-transform probably makes the most sense.

dat$BSS_log <- log(dat$BSS_sum + 1)
ggplot(dat) +
  aes(x = BSS_log) +
  geom_bar()

Exploratory correlations

COPE subscales and SI

M<-cor(dat[c(cope.subscales,"BSS_log")], use = "pairwise.complete.obs")

corrplot(M, method="circle", order="hclust")

COPE subscales and SI (filtering on statistical significance)

Now we want to make a version that filters for significance. To do this, we need to define a function that calculates p-values.

# mat : is a matrix of data
# ... : further arguments to pass to the native R cor.test function
cor.mtest <- function(mat, ...) {
    mat <- as.matrix(mat)
    n <- ncol(mat)
    p.mat<- matrix(NA, n, n)
    diag(p.mat) <- 0
    for (i in 1:(n - 1)) {
        for (j in (i + 1):n) {
            tmp <- cor.test(mat[, i], mat[, j], ...)
            p.mat[i, j] <- p.mat[j, i] <- tmp$p.value
        }
    }
  colnames(p.mat) <- rownames(p.mat) <- colnames(mat)
  p.mat
}

And we use it to make our plot. Nonsignificant correlations (p>.05) how have an X drawn over them.

# matrix of the p-value of the correlation
p.mat <- cor.mtest(dat[c(cope.subscales,"BSS_log")])
corrplot(M, type="upper", order="hclust", 
         p.mat = p.mat, sig.level = 0.05,
         insig="pch", pch=4, pch.cex=1.5,
         pch.col=rgb(0,0,0,.5))

Check the most relevant variables

Look at relationship between SI and the statistically significant variables in some more detail.

ggpairs(subset(dat, select=c(BSS_log,
                             humor,
                             active.coping,
                             planning,
                             emotional.social.support,
                             positive.reinterpretation.and.growth,
                             behavioral.disengagement)),
        lower=list(continuous=wrap("smooth", col=rgb(0,0,0,alpha=.5))))

Multivariate analyses

Fit models.

fit <- stan_glm(BSS_log ~
                Age +
                marital +
                yr_edu +
                race +
                 FCESD + 
                 humor +
                 active.coping +
                 planning +
                 emotional.social.support +
                 positive.reinterpretation.and.growth +
                 behavioral.disengagement,
               iter=4000,
               cores=4,
               data=dat)

Plot 95% credible intervals, with 80% credible intervals shaded.

plot(fit, "areas", pars="beta", 
     prob_outer=.95, prob=.8)

For readability, drop the absurdly uncertain variables from the plot:

plot(fit, "areas", 
     pars=c("Age","yr_edu","FCESD","humor","active.coping",
            "planning","emotional.social.support",
            "positive.reinterpretation.and.growth",
            "behavioral.disengagement"),
     prob_outer=.95, prob=.8)
